g.aria-label: The values we wish to display are 1 and 2. Using a bar graph this can be represented as:
The larger bar is represented as exactly twice the size or area as the smaller bar.
In this example doubling the height doubles the value as the bars remain the same width. However errors often occur when multi-dimensional symbols, such as squares, circles or spheres, are used.
Representing the same values, the common mistake is to scale symbols by height and width:
Otherwise the larger square is represented (and perceived!) as four times the area of the smaller square:
Spheres (and cubes) are also used to represent values. Rather than scaling symbols based on height or area, volume must be used.
Scaling linearly volumetric symbols creates much more error:
The larger sphere has over seven times the volume of the smaller one - rather than twice.
The correct representation scales symbol size based on volume:
Scaling by area is also insufficient, still over-representing the value of 2 as about 3.6.
These errors break the connection between intended value and representational value, communicating false values.
